title.narrative: CHILD RIGHTS SYSTEM BUILDING

description.narrative: Children affected by armed conflict benefit from a strengthened system for monitoring, reporting and responding to violations of child rights in armed conflict, including prevention, rehabilitation and reintegration into the community., which contributes to Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2024, children, adolescents and women, especially the most vulnerable, are protected from violence, exploitation, abuse and neglect in accordance with international standards.

description.narrative: The Iraq Country Task Force on monitoring, reporting and verification of grave child rights violations (CTFMR) continued to lead on the timely and accurate reporting of child rights violations across the country. The CTFMR was able to report 227 incidents of child rights violations. Of these, 224 were verified. 561children formerly associated with armed actors and those at risk were provided with reintegration services, while over 70,000 individuals have increased their knowledge on risks from unexploded ordnance (UXO), explosive remnants of war (ERW) and improvised explosive devices (IED). | Status:On-track | As-of Date:16/01/2022
